segments.text: at 701 gilchrist street just gilchrist in college station talking to bud denton now we're going to stop and see you hope it's working it is the first month of the year january the 20th 1999 bud would you tell us for anybody who might listen or read to this later
give a brief biographical summary of yourself before you came here as an employee.
Because we'll do your student days on another occasion.
All right.
Well, let's see.
My first experience was as a graduate student.
Well, but back up.
Born where?
Oh, I'm sorry.
I thought you said we'd do that later.
Oh, I was born in Lexington, Kentucky.
My father was a coal mine lawyer at Stearns, Kentucky, Stearns Coal and Lumber Company until 1927.
And he was appointed as special assistant to the Attorney General of the United States in Washington, DC.
And we moved there.
My mother died when I was 10.
And we, my sister and I moved to Cleveland, Tennessee to
with my mother's parents and I was raised and went to school there until I completed high school and then I came to Texas and enrolled at A&M.
And what year was that?
September 41.
And then you're here for how long before you go?
Well we were on a three semester deal so I completed two full years and went on into service and of course
deal then was if you left school, you were immediately recalled or called.
We were all, I was one of the first in enlisted reserve in September of 42.
And it was about a month before I was called active too.
And I spent 38 months in the armed forces.
Where?
Camp Walters, Texas.
Camp Blanding, Florida.
in the wonderful peninsula of Italy for 13 months combat, yeah.
And then you came back civilian life here?
Spring of 46.
Now I was married, I should have pointed that out, in 1943.
So I was married when I went overseas and then when we came back to school we were married couple.
And you lived at Dr. McNew's Garage Park.
It was nice.
And then, all right, you graduate when?
Well, I finished in 47 summer, and I was offered a graduate scholarship, they called it then.
It was $100 a month, taught 12 hours of physical ed.
Les Palmer taught 12 hours.
Another guy taught 12 hours for $70, so for $270.
They got 36 hours of teaching, which I enjoyed.
The experience was invaluable.
And then they recommended me...
I had a summer job in the Veterans Testing Service.
We were located first in the old George McCullough Confectionary Building, then they moved us to Bazell.
And we tested veterans and non-students,
I just stayed with it.
Alright, you tested them for what?
Well, just occupational orientation, job opportunities.
Veterans had to be tested.
Alright, this was testing as they were beginning their studies?
Or if they wanted to change majors to college students.
So this was to help them select a major and a professional?
Right.
And then we did a lot of work with skilled and semi-skilled.
So can you give any examples of where the tests obviously succeeded or didn't succeed?
Well, I can from high school, but it's difficult.
Well, college, yeah.
Jack Raines and some of those students that we had at the adjunct later.
That's Jack Raines, the Houston lawyer politician.
Entrepreneur.
Entrepreneur.
Stadium builder.
But anyway, that was the main jest.
And then we had absorption of the Veterans Testing Service, and it was started, I guess, in 49 or 50, the basic division, which was a general studies college, which put us so far ahead.
Of course, Austin has a better background on that than I.
I was integrated into it.
But describe that basic studies.
Well, all entering freshmen who came to A&M in those days were assigned and tested.
We gave a battery of about seven tests, placement tests we called, and talked with the students on the level of English, the level of math.
and staying out of chemistry, you know, that sort of thing.
We offered courses in, now we call it personal development, that's study habits.
And that meant that all those students were, study habits, personal development, or basic psychology, which they still have at A&M, and the occupation study.
And then we had a real high-powered one called Basic 106, which was an orientation to major fields of study.
And we had visiting teachers from biology, chemistry, and so forth.
Describe some of the variety of the talents, or lack thereof, that you all encountered.
Well, of course, the admission requirements at A&M, then, we all always, I think there are
were more difficult then than they may be now.
But the test cutting scores were not in the vote.
The A.C.E.
and S.A.T.
later were tests that were just given and we used those in terms of placement with English achievement and science and math achievement and interest tests.
There must have been some of the students who came from small high schools that were very different from those in the big.
Yeah, a lot of schools in those days offered alternate.
For instance, you took plane geometry this year, algebra two the following year, and if you were out of sequence.
And, of course, A&M had this deal of two algebras, one plane geometry.
And I know when working with athletes later on, athletes later on,
We had a lot of battles with the registrar back then.
Even the math people said, well, what do you need plain geometry for?
And what were the most popular majors then?
Well, it was general curriculum, really.
A lot of kids could play two full years and not lose credit, unless it was something like architecture.
But I did it with athletes later.
In helping them select their courses, he could have a biology course.
And Cliff Ranstall would let them take engineering graphics, for instance, or that ME 101, you remember, that was just kind of a slide rule course, and see how they fell with it.
Of course, we had superb teachers, Medlin and Dobson and all those folks over in biology.
Math was still a... Let's digress on that.
Okay.
Describe some of the great teachers that you remember.
Well, I had a bunch as a student.
Names and what they taught and so forth.
Now, from a personal standpoint?
Either.
Well, from a personal standpoint, Harrison Hurth.
In fact, my family, Alice had Harrison Hurth for a course.
Leslie had him for two courses, and I had him for a course.
You know that we know the Hurths quite well, but let's make believe that I didn't.
What was, what?
Low key.
low key, but what did he do well?
But I was older, you have to realize.
I took his course, it was technical writing in the summer.
And there were a lot of veterans in there, and there were a lot of the younger kids too.
And Harrison had, this guy kept turning up with A's.
And I think it happened about one time, and of course he is so perceptive, I guess he must have felt, there ain't no way.
And so he had us start riding in class.
Of course, personally, he was a neighbor on top of that.
Now, I understand his nickname was Happy Harry.
I never heard that.
Oh, really?
No.
Somebody told me that was his.
And what I know about him, that fits, because he always seems upbeat.
And then I had old Carl Elmquist.
What did he teach?
He taught.
advanced English, Shakespeare, and English Lit.
We knew how the six-day bicycle races were in Chicago.
He hardly ever taught us much.
He was a nice guy.
What about some of the others?
Well, of course, down in PE, I had Seacrest and Colonel Anderson.
Now, you talk about a demanding teacher.
give examples.

He was talking to us one time in his track course about preparation and of course he he just believed that the way to prepare just do it over and over and over and over and he got to the pole vault when he was going through each of the field events and he said the best way to train for the pole vault you remember those dang things
I'd like to have seen some of the kids from that period using the equipment today.
They said, you just have that youngster take that pole and run around that 440 track, not full speed, but just carrying that pole so he can get accustomed to it.
And old Landis taught a basketball course.
And Dr. Landis had just come, it was his first semester to teach here,
And he was a great believer in intramural athletics.
Here, these are all athletes and PE majors.
We're doing basketball.
He said, when in doubt, hook pass, if you ever put that spin.
Of course, he'd get up there and demonstrate it.
We were down in the bowels of the Ware Field House, if you remember that weird place over there by the intramural office.
And I had Dr. Summey, I thought was a classic installer.
We had a bunch of athletes in there, and boy, they did extremely well.
In fact, it was Dean Bolton, it was Brooks.
Dean Brooks called a bunch of guys in, athletes that he'd known before service, and complimented them on their grades.
He said, I just didn't believe you guys could do that well.
Right.
Keep going on faculty.
Well, let's see.
I was always particularly fond of, in counseling students, to know courses where students had difficulty.
You know, Kreiss, do you remember?
Dr. Kreiss.
He just recently retired, I guess.
taught that biology 115.
I felt like as I got to public schools, if you place a teacher where they're comfortable, they'll do a better job.
And I felt like a lot of times that some of those profs wound up teaching courses that they really were disinterested in.
I don't say they took it out on students, but their performance was not good.
Let's see, math.
Well, I was a real scholar when it came to algebra.
When I entered A&M at 41, you had a choice of the 102 or 101.
So I took 102, and I'd had a high school coach taught the advanced algebra in high school.
And we didn't work on stated problems, if you can imagine.
And the first major test, I went in there and we had five questions, four of them stated problems.
And so I was advised that I needed to move back down to 101, which I don't regret.
Class sizes in that era.
Well, I'm going to guess, I would say 30 or under, most of them, English, mathematics.
Science was the larger one.
They had just, I guess they'd always had the large lecture room, but I would guess maybe 100.
My largest class, as I recall, was geology and chemistry.
As you look back on those days when you were a young faculty member, what was the faculty doing here, the academic program, that in hindsight was very positive, strong, good?
You said teaching.
How was that encouraged, that good teaching?
Well, it's hard to say because I
As I got to know the profs, and Alice and I lived right in the middle of them as regular students and played softball league, and I had worked at a swimming pool, so I knew all the children.
It was the fact that they were just, that was their thing, you know.
They came here from Mississippi State, Mississippi, and I guess Alabama, and then probably some through the Midwest.
And they just were dedicated people.
And they didn't pay them anything, I don't think.
Who lived on the, which faculty lived on the campus?
Well, when I was here as a student,
Mary Eccles could tell you because she was talking about that.
Was it just the senior faculty, the old-timers?
That I couldn't tell you.
I know later on when, you know, in the early 50s, I guess they started clearing out that back for the MSC.
I don't know whether that was it or not.
They had that row of faculty houses there.
It came this way and then went down toward where the
vice president, I guess now, or dean, a man, whoever, that little house.
Yeah.
All right.
The counseling program.
It was done when I was a student.
Well, but when you were a young faculty member.
Well, that's where I started.
If I'm a student and I want advice, where did I go?
Oh, to your faculty.
To your teacher.
Oh, yeah.

course I was fortunate because teaching down there as a graduate student in physical ed and then later on in the counseling center I made rounds just like I did in athletics talking to teachers just get my impression of them and you know in those days you could kind of help a kid go over to a course where
He might not have what I'd call the basic skills, but he was a good listener.
And you teach him a few gimmicks on taking notes and things like that.
Who were supposedly, there must have been some teachers that were supposedly easier to get a grade from.
Well, I couldn't say.
Weren't there any myths about, didn't I hear about Dr. Dan the grade point man?
Oh, yeah.
but don't let that fool you.
Dan Russell and Dan Davis both had that reputation.
And then the hardest teacher I ever had, and of course I was
I was really misplaced because I took a geography course under old Doc Schlesser.
Was he here with me?
And he got on this latitude and longitude, and here are all these Air Force guys, you know, and here are two or three of us infantry guys.
We had a compass.
That was about it.
But I tell you what, he could get you to do better.
And of course he lived across the street too.
Alright, you're in the basic division, is that right?
Yeah.
And about how many people were in the... College, basic college?
Yeah.
All the freshmen.
And sophomores and a few juniors up to a 30-30.
30 hours pass, 30 hours grade.
They didn't get out of there with less than a C. So all freshmen started out in the basic division.
They could indicate their major.
They were still, we had, when we first started, I think we had four counselors.
And then it kind of got bigger and bigger, and Les Palmer and Jack Dobson would come over part-time and help.
You mentioned counselors, so
If I'm a student and I needed some academic advice, I could go to one of those.
You came in the front just like you would in a doctor's office.
They took them.
If you had a preference, you might have to wait.
I was backed by the back door, and those kids would come into my office through the back door.
Who were those four?
Do you remember?
Those four counselors?
Yeah, Kingston and...
Al Kingston went to Georgia State.
Bob Jacobs.
I think Cliff was there.
Cliff Ransel.
Yeah.
I can't be sure.
He might come later.
Then we picked up a guy named Perry.
He was a reading specialist and he was kind of a funny little man.
He taught you to read by legal size.
Hand that out.
And, of course, then he brought in another young man who was really superb and reserved.
So we did a lot.
In fact, I made a presentation one time, and Kingston told me, he said, if you're going to do this, you better have a 1,500 sample.
And, of course, we were fortunate because we had all the reading people there.
Now, administratively, who was in charge of the basic division?
John Bertram.
John Bertram.
Retired naval.
Well, he may have been a reserve naval officer.
Of course, he was a shy, retiring guy.
I know the guy was first class, but he kind of gave me the impression he was running that like he might when he was aboard ships.
You can try that on Austin, because he knew him better than I did.
He left, and then we got Bob Com.
Com?
Yeah, he went to Oklahoma State.
K-A-H-M?
No, K-A-M-M. M-M, that's right.
He was a class guy, and he knew guidance.
John was, you know, he was an old ag guy, but not that that's...
Right.
Describe in the early 50s who was president.
Was Mr. Gilchrist still?
I'm not sure when Gilchrist left.
Tom Harrington.
Must have been president because he hired me for the graduate deal and hired me full time for Ed Syke.
Tell me about, make believe I didn't know anything about Tom Harrington and his personality and his talents.
Tell me about it.
Tremendous person.
Chemistry teacher.
I was never fortunate enough because I was a liberal arts student.
But I never heard anybody criticize him.
Ever.
You know, we used to kid
Later on, you know, you got to know him better.
They were always joking about some of the athletes' personnel folders, their grades and everything kind of disappeared in the back of his desk.
You know, you kind of have to be careful because of Biz Harrington still.
But he was really a class man.
He'd call you every once in a while and ask you how you're getting along.
I appreciate that.
What kind of personality?
Outgoing, really.
I laughed.
John Hall talked to the Lions Club.
I wish I invited you to go.
But he was talking about Pinky Downs.
And he is one of my most fond memories.
You could walk across the campus and he always stopped.
Asked me how you doing.
A little chit-chat.
Maybe about athletics or something.
And he'd say,
turned to go and he said, Bud, keep up the good work.
And I just, that just made your day.
You know, official greeter.
Was Dr. Harrington, did you think of him in the early 50s as the key academic decision maker?
Well, see there again, why I said that on the phone, I was more or less removed from it because
In the early jobs, in my early job as the director of that guidance service, I was responsible for the department head of education and psychology.
There were three people in there, and I was the fourth.
You're saying education and psychology was three people?
Yeah.
The department.
And then the next step up would be
Dr. Harrington, who was liberal arts then.
And by this point, the World War II veterans are pretty well gone, early 50s.
The enrollment comes back down to a more reasonable number.
It was a nice, I think you could walk across the campus and you knew most of the, I did, most of the problems.
My dad had a terrible memory.
We'd be walking down the street in Dallas and he'd see somebody and he'd recognize them.
And he'd say, Mr. what's your name?
I'd like for you to meet my son.
And of course, going through this core stuff, you kind of get a little more orientation.
OK.
Were there any changes in the way the basic division operated
during these years?

No there was a lot of competition from the deans because they weren't they didn't have the Austin can give you the nitty-gritty but that they didn't have majors that they could count on and Potts was the toughest and of course he and Heaton must have been blood brothers.
All right tell me about R.C.
Potts.
I liked him personally, but I didn't ever agree with him.
What was his task?
Well, he was dean of agriculture.
Associate dean.
Associate dean.
Yeah, that's right.
I'm sorry.
And so he was the chief agriculture student advisor?
Yeah.
But this was when they got to the School of Agriculture with 30 hours and 30 grade points.
Well, they could have 30 hours and 40 really.
It didn't matter, but they had to have that base.
And I guess when Mr.
Rudder came, he kind of, Kutash used to always tell Rand to get over there and tell him what we're doing.
And this never happened.
Of course, I guess eventually, I guess prior to that, Mr.
Rudder had asked about that study for military.
Right now, so that
POTS and agriculture, who were the... Business was Dan Lowe, the associate.
Did the contact with us too.
We never had any difficulty except... Engineering.
Was.
Cliff Ransom.
Cliff Ransom.
Until he came to us.
I don't remember when he... Was Kutash for all of arts and science or just business?
Dan Lowe.
Dan Lowe?
Was he all of... Business.

all all but just business right who did the rest of arts and sciences Schlesselman yeah and then later Charles okay what were what were the tough courses that okay and history and history you know that you might turn that off I made a study one you're you're talking about
the kinds of students and advising them and how to get them going in the right direction.
Describe that, please.
Well, we were fortunate in those days to have a lot of psychological testing to guide us, plus the high school record.
And you can tell a lot from that.
I found out later on with athletes that if you see a consistency up
or a consistency straight across, or a dipping down of grades and performance in individual subjects.
And you can utilize that to help students select courses that they're going to feel comfortable.
It may be a biology course.
It may be a history course.
And when you're talking to a student, you have to be aware of this type of thing.
We didn't talk much about religion, but some youngsters brought it up themselves and where you see a discipline through their churches or religious background, their family, and their school.
You've got three criteria that I thought.
And we found this working in the early years with opportunity award candidates because we had to interview each one individually before.
before we made a recommendation.
About how many of those per year were awarded?
I'm going to guess 40 or 50 maybe, for the whole school.
Yeah, you'd interview about how many?
Oh, I'd interview 50 myself at least.
Three or four times as many as could be awarded?
Oh, yeah.
And by and large... And it was financial.
That was the base criteria.
And it's hard to say, how do you determine, you know, you've got three children and you've got one parent working, you know, and it's not in a job that you really make a whole lot of money.
Can you recall any of those Opportunity Award winners that you now are proud to single out?
Oh yeah, one is, I guess he's retired by now, it's Carlton Hazelwood.
In fact, later on, as he came through pre-med, three of us wrote letters of recommendation all over the United States, and he couldn't get in medical school.
So he went on and got an advanced degree.
I can't remember.
It was a real specialty.
He wound up teaching down at Texas Medical.
So, you know, you can't use it.
I guess his highest test was a 4% or 5%.
but he had straight A's.
Any others you remember Opportunity Award winners?
Well, no.
He's the only one, you know, they don't compute.
Because I have the impression that Opportunity Award winners have become among the most loyal, generous, grateful Aggies.
Which...
